      "content": "Sure thing! Let me wrap up the risk part and decode that “vibe” reference (because goblins love a good metaphor).\n\n---\n\n### Risks: Fixed vs. Adjustable\n\n- **Fixed‑Rate Mortgage**  \n  *Pros:* Your payment stays the same, so you can plan your budget with confidence.  \n  *Cons:* If market rates go up after you lock in, you’re stuck with that rate—no surprises, but no upside either.  \n  *Goblin analogy:* Think of it like a goblin’s “steady diet” of goblin‑tarts that taste the same every day—predictable, but not always the sweetest.\n\n- **Adjustable‑Rate Mortgage (ARM)**  \n  *Pros:* You often get a lower initial rate (the “fixed” part), and after the adjustment period, your rate can dip or rise with market conditions.  \n  *Cons:* Your payment can fluctuate, so you need to watch the interest rate environment.  \n  *Goblin analogy:* Imagine a goblin who starts by eating a goblin‑tart every day, then after a few days switches to a different flavor that might be sweeter or sourer—fun,",
